From the results of the recent exams this year, we can see that the languages are on the highest board and with the highest approval rates in private schools.
About 68% of the students studying foreign languages obtained an outstanding degree.
The data, compiled from the 74 schools that make up SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained degree of honor in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish, also achieved an outstanding degree.
This shows that Scottish private schools support languages and consider them key skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Today, languages are being given the same consideration as subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in private and all kinds of schools.
A survey carried out by the Employment and Training Commission of the United Kingdom in 2014 indicated that the lack of knowledge of languages constitutes 17% of the reasons why employers are struggling to fill vacancies.
So language skills are increasingly needed to prepare for youth for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalized world, as there are more work opportunities that need languages.
Regardless of the chosen career, learning a second language will have a real advantage in the future with life skills like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will put a bilingual person directly at the head of the competition.
According to a survey of YouGov among more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a percentage of two digits, in this case 15%.
That's why it's so important to invest in a language for children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, gives children more opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, teaching languages differ according to school.
Some schools focus on the most classic modern languages, while others focus on languages that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of their children, private schools always have several languages to choose and specialist teachers in this field.
Scottish private schools specialize in providing a learning environment that equips children and teams with the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future may be.
We cannot deny that at present, in a global business environment, languages remain of vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered as "international communicative skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this diversity and excellence for Scottish youth.
We have to do this.
