Red tide information: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report by the Florida Wildlife Conservation and Fisheries Commission, a general reduction in red tide concentrations is taking place in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the above-mentioned committee, conditions of growing increasingly unequal in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties are being observed, which may mean that concentrations are being reduced.
The red tide extends approximately 210 km from the coast from the northern counties of Pinellas to those of southern Lee.
Concentrations can be found 16 km away from the coast of the Hillsboroug county, but in less places compared to last week.
The red tide was also found in Easter County.
The presence of mid-level concentrations on the coast or away from the coast of Pinellas County last week, bottom and high concentrations away from the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom and high concentrations in or off the coast of Sarasota County, bottom and middle-level concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom and high concentrations in or away from the coast with Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
In the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier are informed that cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
